a couple of key points regarding the clearing of links between nodes in a linked list:

Generational Garbage Collection:

Some garbage collectors, including generational garbage collectors, work more efficiently when objects are cleared from all references. Generational garbage collectors divide objects into different generations based on their age.

Disconnecting all links between nodes helps in scenarios where discarded nodes may exist in more than one generation. By breaking all connections, it ensures that these nodes can be collected more effectively.

Reachability for Iterators:

Clearing links between nodes ensures that even if there is a reachable Iterator or other references, the nodes themselves are not reachable through the linked list structure. This guarantees that the nodes are eligible for garbage collection.

In some cases, objects might be indirectly referenced through iterators or other external references, and breaking internal links helps ensure that the nodes are not retained in memory due to such external references.

In practical terms, whether to clear all links between nodes depends on the specific requirements and characteristics of your application. If you are confident that there are no external references holding onto nodes, you might consider omitting this step for performance reasons. However, if you want to ensure that memory is reclaimed even in complex scenarios, clearing all links can be a conservative and safe approach.So in my  Point of view if you have even singlyLinked list and in program anywhere in any file if you have variable exist that referred directly or indirectly someRaddomVarible = head.next.next.next;   **then even if you null the head and tail the someRaddomVarible  is reachable and connected to links (directly or indirectly) which in turn GC will not delete the connected (directly or indirectly) object in RAM so i will consider better O(n) time complexity for any type of linked list.**

**Singly Linked List:**

    public void clear() {
    
        // Disconnect all links between nodes
    
        LinkedListNode current = head;
    
        while (current != null) {
    
            LinkedListNode next = current.next;
    
            current.next = null;
    
            current = next;
    
        }
    
        
    
        // Set head to null
    
        head = null;
    
    }

**Circular Linked List:**

    public void clear() {
    
        if (head == null) {
    
            return; // Empty list
    
        }
    
        // Disconnect all links between nodes
    
        LinkedListNode current = head;
    
        do {
    
            LinkedListNode next = current.next;
    
            current.next = null;
    
            current = next;
    
        } while (current != head);
    
        
    
        // Set head to null
    
        head = null;
    
    }

**Doubly Linked List:**

    public void clear() {
    
        // Disconnect all links between nodes
    
        LinkedListNode current = head;
    
        while (current != null) {
    
            LinkedListNode next = current.next;
    
            // For doubly linked lists
    
            current.prev = null;
    
            current.next = null;
    
            current = next;
    
        }
    
        
    
        // Set head and tail to null
    
        head = null;
    
        // For doubly linked lists
    
        tail = null;
    
    }

**Circular Doubly Linked List:**

    public void clear() {
        // Disconnect all links between nodes
        LinkedListNode current = head;
        while (current != null) {
            LinkedListNode next = current.next;
            // For doubly linked lists
            current.prev = null;
            current.next = null;
            current = next;
        }
        
        // Set head and tail to null
        head = null;
        // For doubly linked lists
        tail = null;
    }

